The White House has released a fact sheet on the President's Export Control Reform Initiative. The goal of this initiative is to reform the current U.S. export control system in order to enhance national security and counter threats such as the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. The current system is outdated and complicated, with two control lists, multiple licensing agencies, and various enforcement agencies with overlapping authorities. The reform effort aims to simplify and streamline the system by creating a single control list, a single primary enforcement coordination agency, a single information technology system, and a single licensing agency. The Administration has prepared a three-phase approach to implement these reforms, with the first phase focusing on immediate improvements and establishing the framework for the new system. The second phase will result in a fundamentally new export control system based on the current structure, and the third phase will complete the transition to the new system, requiring legislation.